To create the LaTeX code for the diagram you've described, you can use the `tikz` package, which is very powerful for drawing diagrams. Below is the LaTeX code to generate the diagram:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]
    % Define nodes
    \node[circle, draw] (blackhole) {Black Hole};
    \node[circle, draw, below left of=blackhole, xshift=-2cm, yshift=-2cm] (mirror) {Mirror};
    \node[circle, draw, below right of=blackhole, xshift=2cm, yshift=-2cm] (electron) {Electron};

    % Draw arrows
    \draw[->, thick] (blackhole) -- node[midway, above, sloped] {Analog} (mirror);
    \draw[->, thick] (blackhole) -- node[midway, above, sloped] {?} (electron);
    \draw[->, thick] (mirror) -- node[midway, below, sloped] {Map} (electron);
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will produce a diagram similar to the one you provided. Here's a brief explanation of the code:

1. `\documentclass{article}`: This sets up the document class.
2. `\usepackage{tikz}`: This includes the TikZ package, which is used for drawing.
3. `\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}`: This uses the `arrows.meta` library for arrow tips.
4. `\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]`: This starts the TikZ picture environment with a specified node distance.
5. `\node[circle, draw] (blackhole) {Black Hole};`: This defines a circle node named `blackhole` with a label "Black Hole".
6. `\node[circle, draw, below left of=blackhole, xshift=-2cm, yshift=-2cm] (mirror) {Mirror};`: This defines another circle node named `mirror` with a label "Mirror" positioned below and to the left of `blackhole`.
7. `\node[circle, draw, below right of=blackhole, xshift=2cm, yshift=-2cm] (electron) {Electron};`: This defines a third circle node named `electron` with a label "Electron" positioned below and to the right of `blackhole`.
8. `\draw[->, thick] (blackhole) -- node[midway, above, sloped] {Analog} (mirror);`: This draws an arrow from `blackhole` to `mirror` with the label "Analog".
9. `\draw[->, thick] (blackhole) -- node[midway, above, sloped] {?} (electron);`: This draws an arrow from `blackhole` to `electron` with the label "?".
10. `\draw[->, thick] (mirror) -- node[midway, below, sloped] {Map} (electron);`: This draws an arrow from `mirror` to `electron` with the label "Map".
11. `\end{tikzpicture}`: This ends the TikZ picture environment.

Compile this code using a LaTeX editor or compiler to see the diagram.

